<span id="freeTextContainer2825918023967636141">2,392 Ratings · 438 Reviews <br/><br/><b>BURIED</b><br/><br/>I know I know. Pretty HUGE ###&apos;s for a thing to be BURIED. But it&apos;s a language thing (there&apos;s a clause about that in the original BBC=Charter). I dare you just try and find an English=language gr=Review of this thing. [hint :: Andrew&apos;s got one ; Sunny&apos;s got one ;; ReemK10 (Paper Pills)&apos;s got one ;; Huda Aweys as a bilingual=blurb ; one from Nabilah Firdaus ; Naqiuddin Norzemi has got one ;; Tahiya Amin&apos;s got one ;; Amanda Hasan has one ;; Munema&apos;s got one ;; Eui</span>
  <span id="freeText2825918023967636141" style="display:none">2,392 Ratings · 438 Reviews <br /><br /><b>BURIED</b><br /><br />I know I know. Pretty HUGE ###'s for a thing to be BURIED. But it's a language thing (there's a clause about that in the original BBC=Charter). I dare you just try and find an English=language gr=Review of this thing. [hint :: Andrew's got one ; Sunny's got one ;; ReemK10 (Paper Pills)'s got one ;; Huda Aweys as a bilingual=blurb ; one from Nabilah Firdaus ; Naqiuddin Norzemi has got one ;; Tahiya Amin's got one ;; Amanda Hasan has one ;; Munema's got one ;; Euisry Noor's begins with an English word ("AMAZING!") ;; and but then we're already into the realms of Reviews getting single Likes and no Likes which means that these R/reviews don't really count as part of the conversation because that one criteria of the BURIED is that they need to get talk about passed around taken note of recognized at least by title and things of this nature. So. A BURIED book from Arabia.<br /><br />But, you'll see who's already excavated this thing (I mean aside from the scholar [author:Lenn E. Goodman|25969] who's done the <i>serious</i> excavation of making this book available (some more and once again) to the 21st century English reading public) :: volume one of The Novel page 489ff. But you've already checked, haven't you? Moore there says :: "Since Ibn Tufayl wanted to impart a religious philosophy rather than tell an adventure story, we shouldn't fault him for not taking more advantage of his promising topos. [...] <i>Hayy ibn Yaqzan</i> belongs more to the history of Islamic theology than to literature, but it has its place in the history of the novel, both for its own sake and for its influence."<br /><br />And this guy even blames the entirety of The Enlightenment upon it ::<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.cbc.ca/radio/ideas/the-self-taught-philosopher-how-a-900-year-old-arabic-tale-inspired-the-enlightenment-1.4116060">http://www.cbc.ca/radio/ideas/the-sel...</a> <br /><br />And I'm blaming Friend W.D. for bringing this back to my lights and tearing more cash out of my cyber-credit rating (about time to get that window atm re=installed dammit). Thanks a bunch, W.D.....</span>
