<div id="review_912511630" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/912511630" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/912511630?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780917232374" href="/book/show/517597.Ibn_Tufayl_s_Hayy_Ibn_Yaqzan">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=middle-eastern-fiction">middle-eastern-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer912511630" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13754827647727741381">A pleasantly distracting little book, deeply reminiscent of Italo Calvino&apos;s wild fables and Umberto Eco&apos;s philosophical digressions-- albeit written by an Arabic scholar in Medieval Andalusia, and therefore without any of the sleek contemporary irony those guys have. Hayy, the protagonist, is little more than a mouthpiece for the writer&apos;s empiricist system of epistemology, but that doesn&apos;t really matter much. It&apos;s a cool thought experiment, and a charming story.</span>
  <span id="freeText13754827647727741381" style="display:none">A pleasantly distracting little book, deeply reminiscent of Italo Calvino's wild fables and Umberto Eco's philosophical digressions-- albeit written by an Arabic scholar in Medieval Andalusia, and therefore without any of the sleek contemporary irony those guys have. Hayy, the protagonist, is little more than a mouthpiece for the writer's empiricist system of epistemology, but that doesn't really matter much. It's a cool thought experiment, and a charming story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13754827647727741381" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


