<span id="freeTextContainer7312960273071873215">This book has solidified my belief that philosophy is just not the subject for me. The first half, the intro by Lenn Evan Goodman, would be better saved for last. It&apos;s a better idea, in my opinion, to read Ibn Tufayl&apos;s tale first. This will allow you to view the intro in context, leading to a better understanding of the tale that you had just read. I felt so, &quot;What the hell did I just read?&quot; after Hayy Ibn Yaqzan, that I had to read the intro over again. As a lover of history, I was much more in</span>
  <span id="freeText7312960273071873215" style="display:none">This book has solidified my belief that philosophy is just not the subject for me. The first half, the intro by Lenn Evan Goodman, would be better saved for last. It's a better idea, in my opinion, to read Ibn Tufayl's tale first. This will allow you to view the intro in context, leading to a better understanding of the tale that you had just read. I felt so, "What the hell did I just read?" after Hayy Ibn Yaqzan, that I had to read the intro over again. As a lover of history, I was much more interested in the intro itself, which told of the life of Ibn Tufayl, and was much less interested in all the philosophical hypotheses presented. </span>
