    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2902537901" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2902537901" />
    <a title="Jimmy Ele" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30541335-jimmy-ele"><img alt="Jimmy Ele" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1436125044p2/30541335.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2902537901?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jimmy Ele" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jimmy Ele" href="/user/show/30541335-jimmy-ele">Jimmy Ele</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/25634799-ibn-tufayl-s-hayy-ibn-yaqzan">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30541335-jimmy-ele?shelf=foundation">foundation</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2902537901&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2902537901" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5886212178000070179">Great story, the ending is very interesting, especially when Hayy Ibn Yaqzan realizes that the spiritual heights he has reached are uncommon for the common man, even if they seem to be sincerely looking for the path that leads to truth. He realizes that he cannot teach these seemingly well intentioned men the jewels of wisdom that he has gleaned while living alone on the island. <br/><br/>However, after realizing his error at attempting to teach these men, which come to take a dislike to him and his teach</span>
  <span id="freeText5886212178000070179" style="display:none">Great story, the ending is very interesting, especially when Hayy Ibn Yaqzan realizes that the spiritual heights he has reached are uncommon for the common man, even if they seem to be sincerely looking for the path that leads to truth. He realizes that he cannot teach these seemingly well intentioned men the jewels of wisdom that he has gleaned while living alone on the island. <br /><br />However, after realizing his error at attempting to teach these men, which come to take a dislike to him and his teachings (as is evidenced by the quote "But the more he taught, the more repugnance they felt, despite the fact that these were men who loved the good and sincerely yearned for the Truth.") he apologizes to them and lets them know that they should go back to what they were doing before he met them, and to not pay attention to his teachings, since he realizes that even though their spiritual practices are very empty compared to what needs to be done in order to achieve actual higher states of spiritual communion with the divine One, their practices should suffice for them to reach everlasting bliss and life in the afterlife anyways. He leaves them assured that the rituals prescribed by their blessed Prophet, whom he acknowledges as a Prophet sent from the same God, that he came to love and worship, should be good enough.<br /><br />However, he also mentions that those who excel these men in their spiritual practices will outstrip them as far as spiritual rewards are concerned for this life and the next life. Hayy's way of living admits no need for property, and he gets by with the bare minimum of food. He is confounded that there need to be so many laws concerning property and money and inheritance but then Hayy comes to realize that most men are in a state that is no better than unreasoning animals and that to expect them all to be brilliant minded, with great characters, is asking too much of most of them. Hayy does not come off as arrogant, because the only human that he knew was himself his whole life, (until he met Absal) and so he comes to realize that he was gifted with such an immense bounty, in that he was guided on to the path of truth and blessed with spiritual discernment and a really good character (compared to most men).<br /><br />There is a sad foreboding at the end of the book on the part of Hayy Ibn Yaqzan that the majority of people are probably destined to Hell. Here is the most telling quote of the book on how Hayy Ibn Yaqzan feels "Then, class by class, he studied mankind. He saw “every faction delighted with its own.”²⁶⁴ They had made their passions their god,²⁶⁵ and desire the object of their worship. They destroyed each other to collect the trash of this world, “distracted by greed’ til they went down to their graves.”²⁶⁶ Preaching is no help, fine words have no effect on them. Arguing only makes them more pig-headed. Wisdom, they have no means of reaching; they were allotted no share of it.²⁶⁷ They are engulfed in ignorance. Their hearts are corroded by their possessions.²⁶⁸ God has sealed their hearts and shrouded their eyes and ears. Theirs will be an awesome punishment.²⁶⁹" <br /><br />In the end Hayy comes to accept the fact that he can't teach these men and resigns himself to saving himself and his disciple Absal. Absal ends up imitating his way of life on the island and coming close to attaining or actually attaining the same levels of spirituality.<br /><br />The story is very telling in that it argues that the spiritual journey of each man and woman is an individual pursuit, and that most people will not attain to the heights and sublime delights of being of those who are chosen to be close to God. The tale does not come off as an arrogant boastful tale, but more of a cautionary moral tale, in that it shows us the immense character of this fictional man, and then holds a mirror up to most men, and tells them to examine themselves. <br /><br />I came away from the tale feeling thankful that I seem to be (from my own subjective perspective) interested in the spiritual world, God, and the afterlife. However, I also came away from the story feeling like I should be doing more to attain the honor of being of those brought close to God.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5886212178000070179" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


