    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3392631482" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3392631482" />
    <a title="Steven" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8882126-steven"><img alt="Steven" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1515989933p2/8882126.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3392631482?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven" href="/user/show/8882126-steven">Steven</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789753634755" href="/book/show/2046151.Hay_bin_Yakzan">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3392631482" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2457563364772335713">This is one of those works when having a good translation (or better yet read it in the original language) means everything. I got the James Cowan (Azafran Books) version and the reading experience was mediocre. Written in 12th century medieval Spain, Hayy Ibn Yaqzan is a philosophical coming of age story of a boy who&apos;s stranded on an island and raised by a deer. <br/><br/>The tale is incredibly influential, written by the Muslim polymath Muhammad Ibn Tufail, who probably adapted it from an earlier versio</span>
  <span id="freeText2457563364772335713" style="display:none">This is one of those works when having a good translation (or better yet read it in the original language) means everything. I got the James Cowan (Azafran Books) version and the reading experience was mediocre. Written in 12th century medieval Spain, Hayy Ibn Yaqzan is a philosophical coming of age story of a boy who's stranded on an island and raised by a deer. <br /><br />The tale is incredibly influential, written by the Muslim polymath Muhammad Ibn Tufail, who probably adapted it from an earlier version (by Ibn Sina) into an allegorical tale that represents orthodox Sunni Islam's philosophical and mystical principles. <br /><br />Ibn Tufail's version later became a sensation in 18th England and was likely the basis of adventure tales like Daniel Defoe's "Robinson Crusoe." I read both Crusoe and Hayy to do a comparison and the works contrast in that the latter assumes how human beings can't help but search for meaning even if they've never been taught any language or conversed (or met!) another person. Though "Robinson Crusoe" also has a somewhat esoteric element, the story is more about worldly work and adventures.<br /><br />Man's intrinsic need to investigate the True Nature of Reality underpins "Hayy ibn Yaqzan" (literally, "Alive son of Awake"), one of the strangest works in the storied history of Islamic literature. <br /><br />Hayy's doe-mother eventually dies, devastating him. He tries to find out what caused the creature to drop dead all of a sudden. Its bodily parts seem fine, but the machine has collapsed. Eventually, after attempts at dissection, Hayy concludes that "being" is an immaterial endowment that eventually leaves the body. <br /><br />This leads him further on to more complicated inquiries into Nature and why things behave the way they do. Ibn Tufail deftly shows how an innocent mind, without any academic instruction, has the intrinsic tools to search out Life's Ultimate Meaning which, in this case, is the conclusion that a Necessarily Self-Existent Being--God/Allah--is the One cause behind all worldly things. <br /><br />A good translation is vital in that the philosophical and deductive moves that Hayy makes are made more clear to the reader. The Cowan translation I read is good in many part, but totally incomprehensible in other instances (like when Hayy uses the "two lines" thought experiment to demonstrate the absurdity of Infinity in the world). <br /><br />This work is a classic of the Islamic heritage and should be read by an inquiring minds that wants to dig deeper into the Reality of all things. But if you read it in English, make sure the prose is clear and accurate. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2457563364772335713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


