    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3202160886" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3202160886" />
    <a title="William Healey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1841265-william-healey"><img alt="William Healey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500407585p2/1841265.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3202160886?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William Healey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William Healey" href="/user/show/1841265-william-healey">William Healey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780226303109" href="/book/show/7743741-ibn-tufayl-s-hayy-ibn-yaqzan">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3202160886" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13851694902389003295">This is such a good read. It feels like the kind of allegorical narrative Plato might lay out to but with the empirical inquiry of Aristotle. BUT it is done through the lens of the Islamic world. The story starts off with two stories about how the main character is born. Which one is right? The question doesn’t apply. After this the main character’s mother (a gazelle) dies and he dissects it to learn all about biology and other forms of science. You can smell the Aristotle coming off the main ch</span>
  <span id="freeText13851694902389003295" style="display:none">This is such a good read. It feels like the kind of allegorical narrative Plato might lay out to but with the empirical inquiry of Aristotle. BUT it is done through the lens of the Islamic world. The story starts off with two stories about how the main character is born. Which one is right? The question doesn’t apply. After this the main character’s mother (a gazelle) dies and he dissects it to learn all about biology and other forms of science. You can smell the Aristotle coming off the main character’s mother gazelle’s flesh. This main character lives entirely alone after his mother gazelle dies. Reminiscent of Avicenna’s floating man thought experiment. <br /><br />After this the main character spends some time trying to perfect his behavior, and to make sure it is in tune with the natural law he is able to figure out using only his rational mind. Eventually, another man arrives on the island. After some amusing missed encounters, they finally meet. The visitor learns that this wild man is not wild and has in fact decoded a great degree of natural philosophy all on his own! The main character learns that this visitor is a Muslim and the main character learns that the only thing he could not have discovered on his own was the faith of Islam. <br /><br />Soon they both head to the real world, a city of sorts. They are both shocked by the corruption. They try to battle the corruption but it doesn’t work. Eventually, they both leave the city after being disappointed and the two of them go back to the island to live out their days in accordance with natural and religious law. <br /><br />I doubt Descartes, Hume, Kant, and many other Western philosophers ever read this book, but you can tell that a book like this was influential on the whole of Western philosophy even if it wasn’t a direct influence. <br /><br />A delightful read, and one I have my students read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13851694902389003295" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


